  • Method Details

    • world

      public static Geohash world()
      When checking if a geohash is a world geohash, don't use geohash.equals(Geohash.world()); use geohash.isWorld() instead. This is because Geohash.world() is built with a code that uses the default alphabet, and if your geohash has a code that uses a different alphabet, geohash.equals(Geohash.world()) will return false.
      Returns:
      an imaginary geohash which encompasses the entire map, and uses the default alphabet

    • depth

      public int depth()
      Returns the "depth" of this geohash. The world() geohash is by convention at depth 0. All its children are at depth 1, and so on. Depending on your precision and performance requirements, you should use deeper or shallower geohashes. A deep geohash has better precision than a shallow one, but you need more of them to cover the same area. The precision depends on the used GeohashAlphabet. See your preferred GeohashAlphabet implementation's documentation for details.
      Returns:
      A positive integer representing the depth of this geohash
